China Unicom, Hutchison, Kencana, OCI, PLDT: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-03-29T21:07:39Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-29/china-unicom-hutchison-pldt-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  China  Unicom ( Hong Kong ) Ltd. (762 HK): The nation’s
second-largest mobile phone company posted fourth-quarter profit
that more than doubled as the company changed the way it
accounts for handset subsidies. Net income rose to 583 million
yuan ($89 million), from 218 million yuan a year earlier,
according to figures derived from 12-month earnings the Beijing-
based company reported yesterday. Profit exceeded the 339
million yuan median of four analysts’ estimates in a Bloomberg
News survey. Unicom rose 0.2 percent to HK$13.10.  Hutchison Whampoa Ltd. (13)  (13 HK): Billionaire Li Ka-shing’s
biggest company reported full-year profit rose 47 percent to
HK$20 billion ($2.6 billion) after boosting sales from mobile-
phone services, ports, and cosmetics in  Europe , the Americas and
China. This exceeded the HK$16.4 billion average of nine
analysts’ estimates compiled by Bloomberg. Hutchison dropped 2.1
percent to HK$88.80.  Kencana Petroleum Bhd. (KEPB)  : The Malaysian oil and gas
services provider received a 216 million ringgit ($71 million)
contract from the local arm of U.K.-based Petrofac Ltd. to build
well head platforms for the Cendor oil field, according to a
company statement. Kencana added 0.4 percent to 2.58 ringgit.  OCI Co. (010060 KS):  South Korea ’s largest polysilicon
maker won a $904 million order from China to provide the key
material for solar cells, according to a regulatory filing. The
shares climbed 1.4 percent to 486,500 won.  Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL)  : Philippine
Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL PM), the nation’s largest phone
company, said it has offered to buy Digital Telecommunications
Philippines Inc. in a transaction valuing the smaller rival at
74.1 billion pesos ($1.7 billion). Philippine Telephone will get
between 66 percent and 67 percent market share of the nation’s
mobile phone revenue with the purchase, Philippine Telephone
President Napoleon Nazareno said in a press briefing yesterday.  Digital Telecom, which voluntarily suspended trading
yesterday before the announcement, rose 18 percent to 1.83 pesos
when it last traded on March 28. JG Summit Holdings Inc. (JGS
PM), owner of Digital Telecom and which also voluntarily
suspended trading yesterday, advanced 8.2 percent to 24.50 pesos
when the stock last traded March 28. Philippine Telephone was
unchanged at 2,036 pesos.  Solomon Savings Bank (007800)  (007800 KS): The Seoul-based mutual
savings bank is receiving bids to sell a stake in its Gyeonggi
Solomon Savings Bank unit, according to a regulatory filing by
the South Korean company. Solomon will pick a preferred bidder
within few days. Solomon was unchanged at 2,520 won.  To contact the reporter on this story:
